  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering in several complex ways:\n\n1. International Legal Frameworks\n- UN Conventions (Palermo and Vienna Conventions)\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- International standards for combating money laundering\n\n2. Mutual Legal Cooperation\n- Extradition treaties\n- Mutual legal assistance agreements\n- Information sharing between financial intelligence units\n- Cross-border investigations and prosecutions\n\n3. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Establishing common definitions of money laundering\n- Standardizing reporting requirements\n- Creating consistent compliance standards\n- Implementing similar due diligence procedures\n\n4. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- International sanctions\n- Asset freezing and recovery procedures\n- Coordinated investigations\n- Transnational prosecution strategies\n\n5. Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions required to follow international standards\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Risk-based compliance approaches\n\n6. Technical Assistance\n- Training programs for law enforcement\n- Capacity building in developing countries\n- Technology and expertise sharing\n- Supporting legal infrastructure development\n\nThese intersections create a comprehensive global approach to preventing and prosecuting money laundering.",
